# TypeScript style

Applies to all TypeScript in `frontend/` and `backend/` (`.ts` / `.tsx`).

Formatting is enforced by **ESLint Stylistic** (`npm run format` / `npm run lint`), not Prettier.
Prettier cannot express spaces-in-parens or column alignment — do not reintroduce it for TS.

## Spaces inside brackets

Put a space after every opening `{` `(` `[` and before every closing `}` `)` `]`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
foo({bar: 1});
items.map((x) => x);
const arr = [1, 2];

// ✅ GOOD
foo( { bar: 1 } );
items.map( ( x ) => x );
const arr = [ 1, 2 ];
```

Exceptions: empty brackets stay tight — `{}`, `()`, `[]`.

## Align consecutive `=` assignments

In a contiguous block of assignments (or declarations with `=`), pad so all `=` line up.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const id = 1;
const productName = 'Tea';
const price = 10;

// ✅ GOOD
const id          = 1;
const productName = 'Tea';
const price       = 10;
```

Same for class fields / consecutive property assignments:

```typescript
private readonly http     = inject( HttpClient );
private readonly tokenKey = 'token';
private readonly loginUrl = '/api/admin/login';
```

Do not stretch alignment across blank lines or unrelated statements.

Note: `=` alignment is not auto-fixed by ESLint — keep it manually / via agent.

## Align object properties and type fields

In multi-line object literals, type/interface members, and similar key–value maps, pad keys so `:` columns align.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
{
  id: 1,
  productName: 'Tea',
  price: 10,
}

// ✅ GOOD
{
  id:          1,
  productName: 'Tea',
  price:       10,
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
interface Product {
  id: number;
  productName: string;
  price: number;
}

// ✅ GOOD
interface Product {
  id:          number;
  productName: string;
  price:       number;
}
```

Single-line objects/types stay compact: `{ id: 1, name: 'Tea' }`.
